title: Death of a Naturalist
subtitle: Volume one
description: Death of a Naturalist marks the auspicious outset of an acclaimed master. As a first book of poems, it is remarkable for its accurate perceptions and its rich linguistic gifts.

title: The Real Thing
subtitle: A Play
description: A tie-in edition to the upcoming Broadway revival of Tom Stoppard's extraordinary play about love and marriage--the work that has been called "the most moving play" ("The New York Times") he has ever written.

title: Immortality
description: A modern classic, "Immortality" is "ingenious, witty, provocative, and formidably intelligent, both a pleasure and a challenge to the reader" ("Washington Post Book World").

title: The Complete Herbal Handbook for the Dog and Cat
description: Dog and cat owners are becoming increasingly concerned about the saftey of processed pet food and the possible side-effects of over-use of antibiotics and hormone treatments. This new edition, thoroughly revised and updated, covers Natural Rearing, herbal medicine and disease prevention.

title: Even Cowgirls Get the Blues ; My Own Private Idaho
description: Adapted from Tom Robbins' cult novel, Even Cowgirls Get the Blues is a rambunctious epic of cowgirls, FBI agents and ecstatic whooping cranes. My Own Private Idaho charts the pilgrimage of a narcoleptic hustler who is searching for his long-lost mother in a world absent of love.

title: Lawrence Durrell
subtitle: A Biography
description: Traces the life of the English author and discusses how his private world was assimilated into his writings

title: The Last Temptation
description: Novel which portrays Christ as a sensitive human being who is torn between his own passionates desires and his triumphant destiny on the cross.

title: View with a Grain of Sand
subtitle: Selected Poems
description: Selection of poetry of Szymborska - pronounced Shimboorska - the Polish poet who won the Nobel Prize for Literature.

title: The New Life
description: A parable about love, literature and fanaticism. A young university student becomes obsessed with a magical book that delves into the dangerous natures of love and self. Abandoning his studies and his family, he goes with the beautiful Janan on a search for the meaning of the book's darker secrets.

title: Beowulf
subtitle: Translated by Seamus Heaney
description: Composed towards the end of the first millennium of our era, the Anglo-Saxon poem Beowulf is a Northern epic and a classic of European literature. In this new translation, Seamus Heaney has produced a work that is true, line by line, to the original poem.

title: Letters Home
subtitle: Correspondence, 1950-1963
description: This volume collects together Sylvia Plath's correspondence, addressed chiefly to her mother, from her time at Smith College in the early 1950s up to her suicide in London in February 1963.

title: The Poisonwood Bible
description: Told by the wife and four daughters of Nathan Price, a fierce evangelical Baptist who takes his family and mission to the Belgian Congo in 1959, The Poisonwood Bible is the story of one family's tragic undoing and remarkable reconstruction over the course of three decades in postcolonial Africa.

title: Gilliam on Gilliam
description: The candid filmaker turns his his vision inward to explore the motivation behind Monty Python and the Holy Grail, The Fisher King, Twelve Monkeys, and other groundbreaking films. Original.

title: My Century
description: Here, Gunter Grass writes of great events and seemingly trivial ones, of technical developments and scientific discoveries, of achievements in culture, sport, of megolamania, persecution and murder, war and disasters and of new beginnnings.

title: Taxi Driver
description: A drama about a New York cab driver is driven to obsession when he attempts to save a teenage prostitute and embarks on a violent rampage against a world of filth and corruption.

title: Collected Children's Stories
description: Three classic children's stories, Mrs Cherry's Kitchen, The Bed Book and The It Doesn't Matter Suit, collected together in one volume for the first time.

title: Fat Pig
subtitle: A Play
description: Cast ages: adult.

title: The Kid Stays in the Picture
description: "'It's the wildest, most profane, most ridiculously riveting movie memoir ever!' - Newsweek"

title: A Pale View of Hills
description: Etsuko, a middle-aged Japanese woman now living alone in England, dwells on the recent suicide of her elder daughter, Keiko. Despite the efforts of her surviving daughter to distract her thoughts, Etsuko finds herself recalling a particular summer in Nagasaki after the bomb fell.

title: The Unconsoled
description: The Unconsoled is an extraordinary study of a man whose life has accelerated beyond his control

title: The Avignon Quintet
description: An omnibus edition of the five novels published by Durrell in a kaleidoscopic sequence between 1974 and 1985. The books are set mainly in Avignon and the ancient kingdom of Provence, though significant episodes in the quintet are set in the Egyptian desert, Venice, Paris, Vienna and Geneva.

title: Eric
description: Eric calls up a demon to grant him three wishes - but what he gets is the Discworld's most incompetent wizard ...

title: Dark Lord of Derkholm
description: Can the Wizard Derk and his family of human and griffin children save the world from the depradations of the evil Mr Chesney?

title: A Sudden Wild Magic
description: A breathtakingly original, funny adventure of wars, worlds and otherworlds by one of the greatest fantasy writers in Britain

title: The Body
description: In 1960s America, four young boys go on a journey to search for the body of a boy killed by a train. As they travel, they discover how cruel the world can be, but also how wondrous.

title: The Firm
description: Mitch McDeere, a Harvard Law graduate, becomes suspicious of his Memphis tax firm when mysterious deaths, obsessive office security, and the Chicago mob figure into its operations.

title: The Caves of Steel
description: A Classic Robot novel.

title: Faerie Tale
description: A contemporary fantasy novel about the Hastings family who move from California to upstate New York into a ramshackle, old house in a deep wood and become involved in ancient, Celtic magic and occult horror when they are lured into the world of some luminous elfin beings.

subtitle: Odyssey Three
description: Science fiction-roman.

title: Mistress of the Empire
description: Book 3 of the Empire trilogy.

title: The Master of Whitestorm
description: Everyone knew that there was no escape from the slave galleys of the Murghai: once chained to an oar the only release is death. But Korendir refuses to recognize impossibilities and aided by his rowing companion, Haldeth, he leads a desperate but successful revolt.

title: Magician
description: The first book in the Riftwar series.

title: The witches
description: A young boy and his Norwegian grandmother, who is an expert on witches, together foil a witches' plot to destroy the world's children by turning them into mice.

title: Common Ground
subtitle: The Water, Earth, and Air We Share
description: Imagines a village in which there are too many people consuming shared resources and discusses the challenge of handling our world's environment safely.

title: Scary stories 3
subtitle: more tales to chill your bones
description: More traditional and modern-day stories of ghosts, haunts, superstitions, monsters, and horrible scary things.

title: Descriptive Writing
description: Provides ideas and strategies for exploring and teaching descriptive writing in grades 4-8. Includes reproducibles, graphic organizers, mini-lessons and checklists.

title: Persuasive Writing
description: Provides practical ideas and strategies for exploring and teaching persuasive writing in grades 4-8. Includes reproducibles, graphic organizers, mini-lessons and check-lists.

title: P.S. Longer Letter Later
description: Twelve-year-old best friends Elizabeth and Tara-Starr continue their friendship through letter-writing after Tara-Starr's family moves to another state.

title: How Much is that Guinea Pig in the Window?
description: Mr. Day's fourth-grade class has a contest, recycling bottles and cans so that they will have enough money to buy a guinea pig.

title: The lion, the witch and the wardrobe
description: Four English school children enter the magic land of Narnia through the back of a wardrobe and assist Aslan, the golden lion, in defeating the White Witch who has cursed the land with eternal winter.

title: Something Fishy at Macdonald Hall
description: Just as the Headmaster of Macdonald Hall is on the verge of retirement, a wave of practical jokes hits the school, and roommates Bruno and Boots become prime suspects.

title: Run
description: Three teen-agers, thrown together by chance in an isolated house, become increasingly aware of a threat lurking in the darkness outside.

title: Blind Flight
description: Flying with her uncle in his small plane, 13-year-old Debbie who has been blind for about a year must suddenly take control of the plane when her uncle loses consciousness.

title: The Trolley Car Family
description: The Parker's acquisition of an old trolley car results in a delightful summer in the country and a new job for Father.

title: Mrs. Piggle-Wiggle's farm
description: Mrs. Piggle-Wiggle cured a child who could not tell the truth, another who neglected her pets, and a boy who broke everything in sight.

title: Radio Fifth Grade
description: Mayhem breaks out in the fifth grade when the Venice Menace bullies his classmates into letting him become a regular guest on "Kidsview," the school's radio program.

title: Avalanche
description: Chris Palmer is always competing with his brother, a star athlete. During a skiing trip, his rifle sets off a thundering avalanche, leaving Chris buried alive under a mountain of snow.

title: Drina Dances Again
description: When an untimely injury sidelines her from her dancing, Drina joins the cast of a play to keep her mind off her pulled muscle.

title: Blubberina
description: Because of her plumpness, Gwen is not allowed to go up on pointe and the Bunheads have begun calling her "Blubberina," so the girls mobilize to help Gwen lose that extra weight and get her toe shoes.

title: The Littles and the Lost Children
description: Winkie and Tip Small-Fry, two members of a community of small people, become lost in Trash City, the secret community under the town dump.

title: Vampires Don't Wear Polka Dots
description: The third-grade class at Bailey Elementary is convinced that its teacher is a vampire.

title: Werewolves Don't Go to Summer Camp
description: The Bailey Elementary School third graders are greeted at camp by Mr. Jenkins, a growling barefoot creature who eats raw hamburgers and avoids lights.

title: Koko's Kitten
description: Tells the story of a gorilla that communicates with humans using sign language and her love for her kitten, All Ball.

title: The Stranger
description: Drawn to the dark and mysterious Jethro, Nicoletta follows the strange boy to a deserted cave, where she learns his dark secrets.

title: The mystery of the missing cat
description: The mysterious disappearance of a reclusive neighbor's cat involves the Boxcar children in some complicated detective work.

title: These Happy Golden Years
description: Laura has her first experiences as a teacher, and is courted by Almanzo Wilder.

title: On the Banks of Plum Creek
description: Laura and her family move to Minnesota where they live in a dugout until a new house is built and face misfortunes caused by flood, blizzard, and grasshoppers.

title: Mary Anne and the Little Princess
description: Eight-year-old Victoria Kent, distantly in line for the British throne, is spending six months in the states with her parents and Mary Anne is hired as her companion.

title: Good-bye Stacey, Good-bye
subtitle: K
description: Stacey and her parents are moving back to New York! Not only are the Babysitters losing their treasurer but Claudia is losing her best friend.

title: Angels Don't Know Karate
description: Miss Angela Michaels, the new karate teacher in Bailey City, who is also the school crossing guard, is so kind and generous that Melody becomes convinced that she is a guardian angel. Original.

title: The Littles and Their Amazing New Friend
description: On a hill above the Big Valley, the Littles make a discovery that changes their world--tiny people are living in the forest up there!

title: The Meanest Thing to Say
description: When a new boy in his second grade class tries to get the other students to play a game that involves saying the meanest things possible to one another, Little Bill shows him a better way to make friends.

title: The BFG
description: Summary: Kidnapped from her orphanage by a BFG (Big Friendly Giant), who spends his life blowing happy dreams to children, Sophie concocts with him a plan to save the world from nine other man-gobbling cannibal giants.

title: Wanted!
description: When her father is murdered and the police obtain an e-mail confession that implicates her, Alice Robie realizes she will have to flee and prove her innocence. Original.

title: Vesco from Wall Street to Castro's Cuba
subtitle: The Rise, Fall, and Exile of the King of White Collar Crime
description: The account of Robert Vesco, the Kingfish, who bilked investors of $250 million dollars in the early seventies and fled the country just ahead of the Feds, ultimately landing in Cuba.

title: The Changeling
description: Had it not been for the firm belief of two young girls that one of them was a changeling, their lives would have been very different.

title: High performance MySQL
subtitle: optimization, backups, replication and load balancing
description: A guide for MySQL administrators covers such topics as benchmarking, indexes, the stages of processing a query, hardware configuations, copying data to multiple servers, and preventing hardware failure.

title: Hackers & Painters
subtitle: Big Ideas from the Computer Age
description: The author examines issues such as the rightness of web-based applications, the programming language renaissance, spam filtering, the Open Source Movement, Internet startups and more. He also tells important stories about the kinds of people behind technical innovations, revealing their character and their craft.

title: IMovie 4 & IDVD
subtitle: The Missing Manual
description: Explains how to use the Macintosh video production programs to capture and edit digital videos, apply effects, create DVD menus, and burn DVDs.

title: Ruby Cookbook
description: Provides information on using the Ruby programming language, covering such topics as strings and arrays, XML processing, Ruby on Rails, databases, and graphics.

title: MySQL Cookbook
description: Describes the features and functions of MySQL 5.0 along with short code pieces and programming examples.

title: CSS Cookbook
description: Provides information and examples on using CSS to format Web pages, covering such topics as Web typography, links, navigation, page layouts, and Web site design.

title: One Hundred Years of Solitude
description: One of the 20th century's enduring works, Marquez's masterpiece is the ultimate achievement in a Nobel Prize- winning career. Alternately reverential and comical, this novel weaves the political, personal, and spiritual to bring a new consciousness to storytelling.

title: The Barefoot Contessa Cookbook
subtitle: Secrets from the Legendary Specialty Food Store for Simple Food and Party Platters You Can Make at Home
description: Presents a collection of recipes for appetizers, entrees, desserts, and accompaniments

title: Execution
subtitle: The Discipline of Getting Things Done
description: An updated edition of the best-selling reference features a new introduction on how to execute necessary business processes in light of today's challenging economic and financial environment. Cowritten by the author of What the CEO Wants You to Know.

title: Full House
subtitle: The Spread of Excellence from Plato to Darwin
description: Argues against popular conceptions about the nature of progress and evolution, and shows how variety is the essence of life

title: Awakening Intuition
subtitle: Using Your Mind-Body Network for Insight and Healing
description: Explains how to access intuition through the signals given by one's body and feelings in order to attain maximum physical and psychological health

title: Dispatches from the Tenth Circle
subtitle: The Best of The Onion
description: Collects articles from The Onion satirizing people and issues including legislators, religion, small towns, anti-tobacco propaganda, celebrities, and Starbucks.

title: Theater Shoes
description: When their father is captured during the war, three children come to London to live with their grandmother and join all the cousins of their talented theatrical family in a school for stage training.

title: The Princess Diaries
description: With wry, observant wit, crown princess Mia chronicles her rocky first month of high school.

title: Laura Ingalls Wilder Country
subtitle: The People And Places in Laura Ingalls Wilder's Life
description: Presents a portrait of the land and people made famous in the "Little House" series, using family photos, memorabilia, and archival material

title: East of Eden
description: The biblical account of Cain and Abel is echoed in the history of two generations of the Trask family in California

title: Farmer Giles of Ham
subtitle: The Rise and Wonderful Adventures of Farmer Giles, Lord of Tame, Count of Worminghall, and King of the Little Kingdom
description: In the story that inspired Tolkien's Roverandom, a reluctant hero finds himself confronting a foul dragon in order to save his village from destruction.

title: Unweaving the Rainbow
subtitle: Science, Delusion and the Appetite for Wonder
description: Offers an assessment of what science is, how it feeds the human appetite for wonder, and how "unweaving" the mysteries of science can be even more beautiful than the mystery itself.

title: The Letters of J.R.R. Tolkien
subtitle: A Selection
description: Selected letters discuss his books, their meanings, his interests and also reveal his view of the world.

title: J.R.R. Tolkien
subtitle: A Biography
description: Carefully traces Tolkien's life, revealing surprising links between his own experience and his written works, especially The Lord of the Rings trilogy and Silmarillion. Reprint.

title: Clear Light of Day
description: The classic novel by the author of Diamond Dust evokes the traumatic history of India after the departure of the British in a story of a Hindu family in Old Delhi and the complex relationships that develop among four people. Reprint.

title: J.R.R. Tolkien
subtitle: Artist & Illustrator
description: A collection of more than two-hundred reproductions of Tolkien's drawings, sketches, and paintings explores his career as an artist.

title: The Heart is a Lonely Hunter
description: A quiet, sensitive girl searches for beauty in a small, but damned Southern town.

title: Once a Wolf
subtitle: How Wildlife Biologists Fought to Bring Back the Gray Wolf
description: With powerful and rare photos by a former photographer for the National Geographic Society, "Once a Wolf" explores the long-troubled relationship of humans and wolves. The book traces the persecution of the wolf throughout history and also reveals the role scientists have played in wolf preservation. Full color.

title: Stern Men
description: Ruth Thomas, a spunky young woman born into the midst of a feud between two factions of Maine lobstermen, manages to negotiate an end to the conflict. A first novel. Reprint.

title: Colter
subtitle: The True Story of the Best Dog I Ever Had
description: The author shares his memories of his favorite dog, Colter, and the diverse ways in which he transformed the author's life, in a look at the dynamic relationship between humans and dogs.

title: Henry Adams and the Making of America
authors: Garry Wills;Pulitzer Prize-Winning Journalist and Historian Garry Wills
description: A profile of nineteenth-century historian Henry Adams assesses his influence on the study of history, discussing his use of archival sources, firsthand reportage, eyewitness accounts that transformed historical study.

title: Hear the Wind Blow
description: With their mother dead and their home burned, a thirteen-year-old boy and his little sister set out across Virginia in search of relatives during the final days of the Civil War.

title: Midnight is a Place
description: In northern England in 1842, fourteen-year-old Lucas leads a lonely, monotonous existence in the house of his unpleasant guardian until the unexpected arrival of an unusual little girl presages a series of events that completely change his life.

title: Silent Spring
description: Discusses the reckless annihilation of fish and birds by the use of pesticides and warns of the possible genetic effects on humans.

title: The Best American Sports Writing 2003
description: Includes articles chosen from magazines and newspapers on topics ranging from bullfighting to basketball, baseball, and boxing

title: Queen of Scots
subtitle: The True Life of Mary Stuart
description: A new historian of Mary Queen of Scots draws on new sources to shatter various myths surrounding this odd monarch and uncover some of the scandals and political machinations underpinning, and undermining, her throne.

title: The Lord of the Rings
subtitle: The Two Towers : Visual Companion
description: Explores the people, places, and ideas found in the motion picture adaptation of the second part of J.R.R. Tolkien's "The Lord of the Rings."

title: The Lord of the Rings
subtitle: The Making of the Movie Trilogy
description: Discusses the making of the movie trilogy based on J.R.R. Tolkien's "The Lord of the Rings," covering topics including filming locations, special effects, costumes, battle scenes, characters, and music.

title: The Hobbit, Or, There and Back Again
description: A newly rejacketed edition of the classic tale chronicles the adventures of the inhabitants of Middle-earth and of Bilbo Baggins, the hobbit who brought home to The Shire the One Ring of Power.

title: The Lord of the Rings
description: An epic detailing the Great War of the Ring, a struggle between good and evil in Middle-Earth, in which the tiny Hobbits play a key role.

title: The Best American Mystery Stories 2004
description: Presents a collection of mystery stories selected from magazines in the United States and Canada

title: Fergus and the Night-Demon
subtitle: An Irish Ghost Story
description: On his way to town to have some fun, a lazy but clever young man faces a terrible demon, who declares that his time has come.

title: The Fellowship of the Ring
subtitle: Being the First Part of the Lord of the Rings
description: After discovering the true nature of the One Ring, Bilbo Baggins entrusts it to the care of his young cousin, Frodo, who is charged with bringing about its destruction and thus foiling the plans of the Dark Lord.

title: The Lord of the Rings
subtitle: Weapons and Warfare
description: Describes in detail, with over one thousand photographs, the battles, armies, and armor used in the War of the Ring based on J.R.R. Tolkien's "Lord of the Rings" trilogy, including battle plans and character histories and descriptions.

title: JRR Tolkien Companion & Guide
description: An in-depth reference to Tolkien's life and works provides brief alphabetical entries on a wide range of topics that encompass the author's source materials, synopses of his writings, a chronology, analysis of his characters, and the personal and historical influences on his writings.

title: The Maps of Tolkien's Middle-earth
description: Includes four posters depicting Tolkien's world of Middle-Earth with maps from The Hobbit, Beleriand, and Numenor, accompanied by a manual describing the signicance of geographical evolution in the author's works.

title: Understanding the Lord of the Rings
subtitle: The Best of Tolkien Criticism
description: Selected essays on Tolkien's trilogy include W. H. Auden's essay on the hero's quest, C. S. Lewis's piece on the value of myth, Marion Zimmer Bradley's article on hero worship, Tim Shippey's piece on the film trilogy, and much more. Original.

title: Dunk
description: While hoping to work as the clown in an amusement park dunk tank on the New Jersey shore the summer before his junior year in high school, Chad faces his best friend's serious illness, hassles with police, and the girl that got away. Reprint.

title: The Bake Shop Ghost
description: Miss Cora Lee Merriweather haunts her bake shop after her death, until the newest shop owner, Annie Washington, makes a deal with her.

title: Reefer Madness
subtitle: Sex, Drugs, and Cheap Labor in the American Black Market
description: Reports on America's "shadow" economy of illegal drugs, pornography, and illegal migrant workers, arguing that these underground industries continue to grow with government intervention.

title: The Last Shot
subtitle: City Streets, Basketball Dreams
description: Dreaming of a college scholarship and escape from the neighborhood, the talented Abraham Lincoln High School Railsplitters see basketball as their only hope, but the reality of SATS, the NCAA, and college recruitment are tough to overcome.

title: Dark Star Safari
subtitle: Overland from Cairo to Cape Town
description: The author recounts his odyssey down the length of Africa, from Cairo to South Africa, describing the bad food, many delays, discomforts, and dangers of his trip, along with the people and places of the real Africa.

title: The Best American Sports Writing 2006
description: Includes articles chosen from magazines and newspapers on topics ranging from bullfighting to basketball, baseball, and boxing

title: Trip to the North Pole
authors: Ellen Weiss;Robert Zemeckis;William Broyles;Chris Van Allsburg
description: On Christmas eve, a young boy joins some other children on a magical train ride to the North Pole, in an adaptation of the new movie being released this holiday season. Original.

title: Fun Home
subtitle: A Family Tragicomic
description: A memoir done in the form of a graphic novel by a cult favorite comic artist offers a darkly funny family portrait that details her relationship with her father--a funeral home director, high school English teacher, and closeted homosexual.

title: The Lord of the Rings Complete Visual Companion
description: Photographs, screenshots, and images from all three films provide a visual compendium of the film trilogy "The Lord of the Rings," documenting the varied characters and locales as seen through Peter Jackson's vision of Middle-earth.

title: The Heart is a Lonely Hunter
description: A quiet, sensitive girl searches for beauty in a small, but damned Southern town.

title: Firefighters in the Dark
description: While in bed at night, an imaginative child hears sirens from the nearby fire station and creates fantastic stories about what the firefighters are going to do.

title: Tolkien And The Great War
subtitle: The Threshold Of Middle-earth
description: The author focuses on a little-discussed aspect of J. R. R. Tolkien's life--his harrowing experiences in the trenches during World War I--revealing how the death of two comrades in particular influenced his later life and literary career. Reprint.

title: The Two Towers
subtitle: Being the Second Part of The Lord of the Rings
description: After losing Gandalf and being divided from their other companions during an Orc attack, Frodo and Sam continue towards Mordor, Land of the Enemy, to destroy the Ring, accompanied only by a mysterious figure that follows them.

title: The Lord of the Rings: The return of the king
The Best American Travel Writing 2006
description: Presents an anthology of the best travel writing published in the previous year, selected from magazines, newspapers, and web sites.

title: The Best American Spiritual Writing 2006
description: A selection of the finest spiritual writing of the year offers essays and articles on faith, spirituality, and their influence on politics, creativity, literature, and other fields, reflecting Christian, Muslim, Jewish, Buddhist, and other diverse perspectives.

title: The Polar Express
description: A magical train ride on Christmas Eve takes a boy to the North Pole to receive a special gift from Santa Claus, in a slip-cased gift edition of the holiday classic. A Caldecott Medal Book.

title: Mcdougal Littell Science
subtitle: Earth Science
authors: James Trefil;Houghton Mifflin Company;Rita Ann Calvo;Kenneth Cutler

title: Bury the Chains
subtitle: Prophets and Rebels in the Fight to Free an Empire's Slaves
description: Offers an account of the first great human rights crusade, which originated in England in the 1780s and resulted in the freeing of hundreds of thousands of slaves around the world.

title: The Ancestor's Tale
subtitle: A Pilgrimage to the Dawn of Evolution
description: A renowned biologist provides a sweeping chronicle of more than four billion years of life on Earth, shedding new light on evolutionary theory and history, sexual selection, speciation, extinction, and genetics.

title: The Lord of the Rings Sketchbook
description: A large-format collection of drawings and paintings culled from the illustrated edition of the Lord of the Rings and the recent film trilogy includes more than 150 illustrations from the author as well as twenty full-color plates made for Peter Jackson's production company.

title: Gossamer
description: While learning to bestow dreams, a young dream giver tries to save an eight-year-old boy from the effects of both his abusive past and the nightmares inflicted on him by the frightening Sinisteeds. 100,000 first printing.

title: In the Lake of the Woods
description: Pursued by rumors of the atrocities he committed in Vietnam, a politician and his wife seek refuge in a lakeside cabin in northern Minnesota, where a mystery unfolds when the wife mysterious vanishes into the nearby wilderness. Reprint.

title: Chew on this
subtitle: Everything You Don't Want to Know about Fast Food
description: A behind-the-scenes look at the fast food industry.

title: Three Nights in August
subtitle: Strategy, Heartbreak, and Joy, Inside the Mind of a Manager
description: The Pulitzer Prize-winning author of Friday Nights Lights chronicles a three-game series between baseball rivals Cardinals and Cubs, focusing particular attention on the stars of the game, Albert Pujols, Sammy Sosa, Mark Prior, and Scott Rolen. Reprint.

title: Extremely Loud and Incredibly Close
description: Oskar Schell, the nine-year-old son of a man killed in the World Trade Center attacks, searches the five boroughs of New York City for a lock that fits a black key his father left behind.

title: The Hungry Tide
description: Presents a novel of life in modern India, chronicling the interwoven journey of an American marine biologist and a Delhi businessman who travel to the remote Sundarban islands.

title: King Leopold's Ghost
subtitle: A Story of Greed, Terror, and Heroism in Colonial Africa
description: In "an enthralling story, full of fascinating characters, intense drama, high adventure, deceitful manipulation, courageous truth-telling, and splendid moral fervor" ("Christian Science Monitor"), Hochschild tells the story of King Leopold of Belgium, a megalomaniac of monstrous portions. 31 photos. Map.

title: The Chosen
subtitle: The Hidden History of Admission and Exclusion at Harvard, Yale, and Princeton
description: A professor of sociology at the University of California presents the findings of his survey of admissions at Princeton, revealing a century of exclusion that cuts to the core of the American experience, while raising important questions about the stratification of higher education in America. Reprint.

title: Children of Húrin
description: A fantasy adventure saga set in the early days of Middle-Earth features humans and elves, dwarves and dragons, orcs and dark sorcerers clashing in an epic battle between good and evil.

title: On Certainty
description: Written over the last 18 months of his life and inspired by his interest in G. E. Moore's defence of common sense, this much discussed volume collects Wittgenstein's reflections on knowledge and certainty, on what it is to know a proposition for sure.

title: Liberals and Communitarians
description: This is a substantially updated edition of the established guide to this key debate in modern political philosophy.

title: Philosophical Investigations
subtitle: The German Text, with a Revised English Translation 50th Anniversary Commemorative Edition
description: The Philosophical Investigations of Ludwig Wittgenstein (1889-1951) present his own distillation of two decades of intense work on the philosophies of mind, language and meaning.

title: The Mystery of the Ancient Pyramid (Cairo, Egypt)
subtitle: Cairo, Egypt
description: Mimi, Papa, Grant and Christina find themselves in Egypt trying to solve a mystery involving a missing mummy, a curse and a mad archaeologist.

title: Self-made Man
subtitle: One Woman's Journey Into Manhood and Back Again
description: A Los Angeles Times columnist recounts her eighteen-month undercover stint as a man, a time during which she underwent considerable personal risks as she worked a sales job, joined a bowling league, frequented sex clubs, dated, and encountered firsthand the rigid codes and rituals of masculinity. 80,000 first printing.

title: The Roald Dahl Treasury
description: Presents selections from the author's children's books arranged in such categories as "Animals," "Magic," "Family, friends and foes," and "Matters of importance"

title: Helen of Troy
description: Married at a tender age to the Spartan king Menelaus, the beautiful Helen bears him a daughter and anticipates a passionless marriage before falling in love with the Trojan prince Paris, with whom she flees to Troy with devastating consequences.

title: Dust
subtitle: A Richard Jury Mystery
description: Richard Jury investigates the death of a wealthy bachelor with a mysterious past who was last seen in a club named Dust.

title: The Mistress's Daughter
description: A woman who was adopted as a newborn recounts her experience of meeting her birth parents, describing how adoption affected her sense of identity, her efforts to learn about her late birth mother's personal life, and her discouragement with her birth father's unwillingness to invite her into his family.

title: Vinyl Cafe Diaries
description: The further adventures of Dave and Morley.

title: Death of a Salesman
description: Reprint of the 1967 ed. published by Viking Press, New York.

title: Spycatcher
subtitle: The Candid Autobiography of a Senior Intelligence Officer
description: The former assistant director of MI5 offers an account of British Intelligence, including his work on the Ring of Five and exposing Soviet espionage and the conspiracy to oust Harold Wilson from the office of Prime Minister in the 1970s

title: The Adventures of Pippi Longstocking
description: A collection of three previously published books: Pippi Longstocking, Pippi goes on board, and Pippi in the South Seas.

title: Artemis Fowl
subtitle: The Eternity Code
description: Twelve-year-old villain, Artemis Fowl, is the most ingenious criminal mastermind in history. His bold and daring plan is to hold a leprechaun to ransom; but he's taking on more than a bunch of fairies when he kidnaps Captain Holly Short of the Lep-Recon (lower elements police reconnaissance unit).

title: Echo Platoon
description: With Iran and Russia angling to take over oil resources in the Caspian Sea, the Navy SEALs, accompanied by Major Jessica Van Pachen and the Rogue Warrior, are sent in to protect American interests in the region. Reprint.

title: Pieces
description: Collects short stories written by winners of MTV's "Write Stuff" competition, expressing change and life's experiences, such as broken engagements, doomed relationships, and reunions between high school friends.

title: The Law of Enclosures
description: The story of a forty-year marriage follows the turbulence and joys shared by Henry and Beatrice, who in the emotional fallout of their relationship discover that they still have mutual feelings of love for each other. Reprint.

title: Private Parts
description: An autobiography by the original "shock jock" shares his observations on politics, current affairs, women, and the entertainment business

title: The Millionaire Next Door
description: Reveals that the accumulation of wealth in the United States is most often done through hard work, diligent savings, and living a frugal lifestyle

title: The Tenth Man
description: Held prisoner by the Germans during World War II, a wealthy French lawyer is chosen to die but makes a cowardly trade for his life, a decision that he must pay for as a free man. Reprint.

title: The Gun Seller
description: A spoof of the spy genre set in Britain features a drifter who orchestrates a magnificent caper involving the CIA, international terrorists, arms dealers, a high-speed chase on skis, and buxom, blonde beauties.

title: The October Horse
description: Now in paperback--the sweeping epic of ancient Rome from the #1 bestselling author of "The Thorn Birds" that brings to life Gaius Julius Caesar during the last days of the Roman Republic.

title: Bag of Bones
description: Plagued by vivid nightmares of the summer house he had shared with his late wife, grieving widower Mike Noonan returns to his former Maine getaway, only to find a town in the grip of a ruthless millionaire and tormented by a series of ghostly visitations. Reprint.

title: Wither
description: When a quiet college town is invaded by bloodhungry demons, a savvy college freshman teams up with a local amateur historian to uncover a terrifying crime in the town's past. Reprint.

title: Clive Cussler and Dirk Pitt Revealed
description: Includes photographs, summaries of each Dirk Pitt novel, an interview with Cussler, and Dirk Pitt trivia questions

title: All Through the Night
description: Alvirah, an amateur detective, and her husband Willy investigate when an after-school shelter for neighborhood kids is prevented from moving into a neighboring building by a couple living there who claim to have inherited it

title: The Fuck Up
description: A dark comedy of urban life features an aspiring, but incompetent, writer, who is dumped by his girlfriend, fired for asking for a raise, and stumbles into a robbery

title: How to Stop Worrying and Start Living
description: The first trade paperback edition of the classic guide to conquering the fears and worries that prevent individuals from living full and happy lives offers practical advice on how to eliminate business and financial anxieties, turn criticism into an advantage, avoid fatigue, and more. Reprint. 25,000 first printing.

title: Present Tense
description: After the Enterprise is hurtled three days into the past by the explosion of a dying world, expeditions to the surface of that world take on a perilous new meaning when Captain Kirk and Dr. McCoy mysteriously vanish.

title: Carrie
description: Presents the unnerving story of a terribly ostracized young girl with supernatural powers of telekinesis.

title: Salem's Lot
description: In a classic tale of horror by Stephen King, a man returns to his hometown of Jerusalem's Lot, Maine, only to find it infested with vampires. Reprint.

title: Ice
description: Ice Goodman, a troubled young girl, must draw on her extraordinary singing voice to escape the tragedy, deception, and her mother's jealousy that threaten to destroy her world. Original.

title: The Living Blood
description: Struggling to rebuild her life after the disappearance of her husband and the death of her oldest daughter, Jessica discovers that her other daughter inherited her father's immortality and sets out for Africa for guidance.

title: Venice: Lion City
subtitle: The Religion of Empire
description: A unique historical perspective on Venice, one of the world's most fascinating cities, during the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries, is told through the art, which is connected to its imperial religion and which details the labor, warfare, government, prayer, and discipline of the time. Reprint.

title: Uncle Shelby'S Abz Book
description: Writing for an adult audience, the popular children's book author presents a humorous satire of alphabet books.

title: Confessions of an Actor
subtitle: Laurence Olivier an Autobiography/#07444
description: An autobiography by the English actor discusses his theatrical and film career and offers a candid account of his personal life, focusing on his relationship with actress Vivien Leigh

title: Soldier, general of the army, president-elect, 1890-1952
Mornings on Horseback
subtitle: The Story of an Extraordinary Family, a Vanished Way of Life and the Unique Child Who Became Theodore Roosevelt
description: Examines the life of Theodore Roosevelt from age ten to twenty-seven, focusing on the influence of his family relationships and experiences on his growth to manhood

title: The Canterbury Tales of Geoffrey Chaucer
Guilty as Charged
subtitle: A Mystery Writers of America Anthology
description: An anthology of courtroom drama and whodunit suspense includes short works by such popular authors as John Lutz, Stuart Kaminsky, Jay Brandon, John Jakes, Lia Matera, and Bill Brozini. Original.

title: Sharp Edges
description: A museum curator and a rough-hewn private investigator enter the sinister, high-stakes world of priceless art, where they discover that the most valuable commodity is knowing whom to trust

title: Alien Stars
authors: C. J. Cherryh;Haldeman, Joe W;Mitchell, Elizabeth;Zahn, Timothy
description: Three notable science fiction authors pit men and women against difficult alien races in their respective stories of extraterrestrial wars of the future

title: The Man Who Sold The Moon
description: Comprehensive Teacher's Guide available.

title: Field Guide to Home Buying in America
description: Covers home selection, financing, real estate agents, negotiation, contracts, title, closing, insurance, and moving

title: Wind Child
description: Nancy Harding uses her storytelling gifts to depict a young woman who would defy every tradition of her male-dominated society--and triumph! Set against the ancient world of the Scythian tribes of 513 B.C., Wind Child is a passionate, exhilarating, unforgettable tale.

title: Anne Frank Remembered
subtitle: The Story of the Woman who Helped to Hide the Frank Family
description: The reminiscences of Miep Gies, the woman who hid the Frank family in Amsterdam during the Second World War, presents a vivid story of life under Nazi occupation.

title: Ghost Story
description: Questions arise concerning the connections between a strangely detached young girl's captivity in a seedy Florida motel, a death that occurs at a party for a visiting actress, and a young California instructor's obsession with one of his students

title: Blue World
description: Presents a collection of tales of the macabre accompanied by the novella "Blue World"

title: Cyclops
description: A secret moon base called the Jersey Colony constructed by a group of powerful Americans and a secret American/Cuban pact between the president and Fidel Castro challenges all of Dirk Pitt's incomparable skills

title: The Seven Habits of Highly Effective People
subtitle: Restoring the Character Ethic
description: A presentation of a holistic, integrated, principle-centered approach for solving personal and professional problems.

title: Shakespeare's Sonnets
description: Presents a collection of 154 of Shakespeare's sonnets and includes detailed notes on the sonnets and an overview of Shakespeare's life and literary impact.

title: The Color Purple
description: The lives of two sisters--Nettie, a missionary in Africa, and Celie, a southern woman married to a man she hates--are revealed in a series of letters exchanged over thirty years

title: Night of the Fox
description: When an American officer who knows the time and place of the D-Day invasion disappears in German-occupied Jersey, the Allies choose Harry Martineau to direct the rescue mission

title: Wolf's Hour
description: This book is a remarkable tale of pulse-pounding excitement with a uniquely sympathetic, fascinating portrait of the werewolf as nobel warrior-and conflicted being. Complex, compelling and utterly real.

title: Journey To Ixtlan
description: Drawing from his ten-year apprenticeship in sorcery, the author discusses the philosophy and teachings of his instructor, a Yaqui Indian

title: Second Ring of Power
description: Transformed by Don Juan from a bent, gray-haired old woman into a sensual sorceress whose mission is to test Castaneda, Dona Soledad turns her mysterious and awesome powers against Castaneda in a struggle that nearly consumes him

title: Power of Silence
description: Carlos recollects more of the teachings of Don Juan, including the true importance and meaning of sorcery and magic, and the illusory nature of all realities

title: Fire from Within
description: The author depicts his instruction by the sorcerer Don Juan in the mystical religious concepts and practices of the Mexican Indians

title: Tales of Power
description: Carlos is taught his last lessons by Don Juan before he and Don Genaro disappear, including the concepts of naugal and tonal, and the ways of the impeccable warrior

title: The Story of Philosophy
description: Examines the history of speculative thought by focusing on such dominant personalities as Plato, Bacon, Spinoza, Kant, Schopenhauer, and Nietzsche

title: Long Dark Tea-Time of the Soul
description: When a passenger check-in desk shoots through the roof of a terminal at Heathrow Airport in flames, Dirk Gently investigates the cosmic forces at play

title: Boy's Life
description: The witnesses to a horrific murder, Cory Mackenson and his father investigate and come face to face with the vicious Blaylock clan, a secret society united by racial hatred, and a reptilian creature inhabiting the river. Reissue.

title: Joy Within
description: Carefully avoiding and particular religious or spiritual point of view, this book offers a practical step-by-step guide to meditation for beginners. It explains what meditation is and details its many benefits, including inner peace, stress reduction, relaxation, and joy. Illustrated.

title: Mystery Walk
description: As Billy Creekmore and Wayne Falconer, two young men with remarkable psychic gifts, learn to use their powers, they and their world are threatened by the machinations of their elusive, nightmarish enemy, the Shape Changer. Reissue.

title: Principle Centered Leadership
description: The author invites business readers to center their professional lives around principles of excellence and quality and discusses the six conditions of effectiveness and the patterns of organizational excellence

title: In the Name of Love
subtitle: Ann Rule's Crime Files
description: A collection of true crime cases includes the case of Jerry Harris, a self-made millionaire whose disappearance prompted his wife's eight-year search for answers

title: The Good Earth
description: A story of a Chinese peasant and his passionate, dogged accumulation of land and more land, while weathering famine and drought and revolution.

title: Star Trek
subtitle: Log Seven, Log Eight, Log Nine, Log Ten
description: Four exciting stories taken from the log books of the USS Enterprise - The Counter-Clock Incident, The Eye of the Beholder, Bem and Slaver Weapon.

title: Lincoln at Gettysburg
subtitle: The Words that Remade America
description: An account of Lincoln's revolutionary speech describes how, in the space of 272 words, the President brought to bear the rhetoric of the Greek Revival, the categories of transcendentalism, and the imagery of the Rural Cemetary Movement

title: Forever After
description: The heroes of a millennium-long battle against the forces of evil prepare to enjoy life after winning the war, unaware that they have unearthed four mantic objects whose combined powers unleash chaos throughout the world. Original.

title: The Ship Avenged
description: Hoping to settle old scores with the Kolnari who destroyed her home and with an unscrupulous uncle, Joat is challenged to overcome a "breakout" disease that destroys its victim's minds and is threatening the entire universe.

title: The Free Bards
description: Comines the stories of Rune, the greatest violinist who played the Ghost of Skull Hill to sleep; Robin who must recruit the Ghost to aid their cause; and Nightingale who joins forces with T'fyrr, a nonhuman with the face of a raptor

title: Berserkers
subtitle: The Beginning
description: Complete at last in one volume--the beginning of the war against the berserkers! The death machines are programmed to destroy all life in the Galaxy. But one branch of Galactic humanity, descended from a world called Earth, stands in the way.

title: What Jane Austen Ate and Charles Dickens Knew
subtitle: From Fox Hunting to Whist-the Facts of Daily Life in Nineteenth-Century England
description: Essays provide a view of British life during the nineteenth century

title: Daily Reflections for Highly Effective People
subtitle: Living THE SEVEN HABITS OF HIGHLY SUCCESSFUL PEOPLE Every Day
description: Provides a daily reading program that keys on the author's guidelines to personal fulfillment and success and offers inspiration, insights, and motivational guidance

title: American Tragedy
subtitle: Kennedy, Johnson, and the Origins of the Vietnam War
description: Documents the origin of American involvement in the Vietnam War and how the policies in the Eisenhower, Kennedy, and Johnson administrations led to war.

title: This Craft of Verse
description: Transcribed from recently discovered tapes, this work stands as a deeply personal yet far-reaching introduction to the pleasures of the word, and as a first-hand testimony to the life of literature. 1 halftone.

title: The Gardens of Emily Dickinson

title: Rebecca's Revival
description: The remarkable story of Rebecca Protten, a Caribbean slave who helped inspire the rise of black Christianity in the Atlantic world, is revealed in this account of her evangelical efforts on three continents.

title: The Writer of Modern Life

description: In these essays, Benjamin challenges the image of Baudelaire as late-Romantic dreamer, and evokes instead the modern poet caught in a life-or-death struggle with the forces of the urban commodity capitalism that had emerged in Paris around 1850.

title: Ancilla to the Pre-Socratic Philosophers
subtitle: A Complete Translation of the Fragments in Diels, Fragmente Der Vorsokratiker
description: This book is a complete translation of the fragments of the pre-Socratic philosophers given in the fifth edition of Diels, Fragmente der Vorsokratiker.

title: Ethics and the Limits of Philosophy
description: Toward the goal of reorienting ethics away from rigid systems and toward the individual, a noted philosopher criticizes systematic moral theory from Kant on and elucidates a provocative alternate view

title: The Art of Shakespeare's Sonnets
description: Analyzes all of Shakespeare's sonnets in terms of their poetic structure, semantics, and use of sounds and images

title: Playing in the Dark
subtitle: Whiteness and the Literary Imagination
description: Examines the effect of a racially divided society on ninteenth century American writings, and discusses works by Poe, Hawthorne, Melville, and Twain

title: The Principles of Psychology
subtitle: The principles of psychology / William James. Notes, appendixes, apparatus, general index
description: Presents an authoritative new edition of the classic text that corrects hundreds of errors and incorporates all of the changes James made in the eight printings he supervised, along with revisions and new material the author added to his own annotated copy.

title: The Roman Empire
description: Offers a history of the Roman Empire from 44 B.C. to A.D. 235.

title: Sex and Reason

title: Sor Juana, Or, The Traps of Faith
description: A life of the seventeenth-century poet, intellectual, and feminist who became a nun and eventually gave up secular learning, places her in her times and in Spanish intellectual tradition, and examines the contradictions in her personality.

title: Sources of the Self
subtitle: The Making of the Modern Identity
description: Discusses contemporary notions of the self, and examines their origins, development, and effects

title: Summer for the Gods
subtitle: The Scopes Trial and America's Continuing Debate Over Science and Religion
description: Provides a modern perspective on the legal and historical influence of the 1925 Scopes trial, the landmark case about teaching evolution in the classroom

title: Time's Arrow, Time's Cycle
subtitle: Myth and Metaphor in the Discovery of Geological Time
description: Examines scientific theories pertaining to the measurement of earth's history

title: The Visible Hand
description: Examines the processes of production and distribution in the U.S. and the ways in which their management has become increasingly systematized

title: Wittgenstein on Rules and Private Language
subtitle: An Elementary Exposition
description: In this book Saul Kripke brings his powerful philosophical intelligence to bear on Wittgenstein's analysis of the notion of following a rule.

title: The World, the Text, and the Critic
description: Argues that contemporary critics force works of literature to fit their theories and examines the impact of Marxism, linguistics, psychoanalysis, and structuralism on literary criticism

title: Epictetus

description: These volumes contain the teachings ("Discourses") of the slave-philosopher Epictetus (55 A.D-135 AD). Also included in volume 2 are "Fragments", additional pieces from other (now lost) books of the "Discourses"; and "The Encheirdion", a collection of practical precepts for stoicism which can be seen as a handbook for life.

title: The Art of Love, and Other Poems

title: Babrius and Phaedrus
description: Babrius's humorous and pointed fables in Greek verse probably date from the first century CE. From the same period come the lively fables in Latin verse written by Phaedrus, which satirize social and political life in Augustan Rome.

title: Never Let Me Go
description: A gothic tour de force. A meditation on mortality and lost innocence: a portrait of adolescence as that hinge moment in life when self-knowledge brings intimations of one's destiny.

title: Gift from the Sea
description: A woman's reflections on life, its stages, and its states, comparing them with the natural treasures of life in the sea

title: Doctor Faustus
description: (Book Jacket Status: Not Jacketed) Introduction by T. J. Reed; Translation by H. T. Lowe-Porter

title: Toni Morrison
description: Presents six novels by American Nobel laureate Toni Morrison--"Beloved," "Sula," "Jazz," "Tar Baby," "Song of Solomon," and "The Bluest Eye"--Which explore the African-American experience in America's predominantly white culture.

title: The Aeneid
description: Virgil's poem about the adventures of Aeneas after the fall of Troy

title: If on a Winter's Night a Traveler
description: Ten different and thoroughly dissimilar novels intertwine as the beginning of each book, interrupted at a critical moment of suspense, leads into yet another novel reflecting yet another literary mode

title: The Stranger
description: An ordinary man is unwittingly caught up in a senseless murder in Algeria.

title: Crime and Punishment
description: A man must endure relentless physical and mental punishments as retribution for his act of murder

title: The Complete Collected Poems of Maya Angelou
subtitle: Poems (1965-1992)
description: Presents a definitive collection of poetry from Angelou's previous anthologies--Just Give Me a Cool Drink of Water, Oh Pray my Wings Gonna Fit Me Well, And Still I Rise, I Shall Not Be Moved, On the Pulse of Morning, and Shaker, Why Don't You Sing? 50,000 first printing.

title: Gargantua and Pantagruel
description: A fantasy of life amongst the monks and friars of 16th-century France which remains a satirical and comic classic. Rabelais espouses a positive view of life in which tolerance, goodness, understanding and wisdom are opposed to dogmatism, pride and cruelty.

title: In the Kitchen with Rosie
subtitle: Oprah's Favorite Recipes
description: With 50 recipes and 8 pages of full-color photographs by Micheal McLaughlin.

title: Rabbit Angstrom
subtitle: A Tetralogy
description: Four novels trace the life of Harry "Rabbit" Angstrom against the changing American society from the sixties to the eighties

title: The Sibley Field Guide to Birds of Western North America
description: A guide for bird enthusiasts specifically designed for use in the field features descriptions of 703 species of birds from west of the Rocky Mountains, and illustrations that depict species from different views.

title: Swann's Way
description: The narrator interrupts reminiscences about his childhood spent in the late-nineteenth-century France to recall the affair which a friend of the family carries on with young Odette de Crecy.

title: The Sound and the Fury
description: Depicts the troubled childhood of Jason, Quentin, Caddy, and Benjy Compson, members of a southern family.

title: Stars in Their Courses
subtitle: The Gettysburg Campaign, June-July 1863
description: Recreates the Battle of Gettysburg from both the Confederate and Union perspectives

title: The Poetry and Short Stories of Dorothy Parker
description: Ketubot Part I

title: Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas and Other American Stories
description: Contains the journalist's classic account of his visit to Las Vegas, and includes three companion pieces

title: Blood Meridian, Or, The Evening Redness in the West
description: Based on incidents that took place in the southwestern United States and Mexico around 1850, this novel chronicles the crimes of a band of desperados, with a particular focus on one outlaw, known as "the Kid," a boy of fourteen. 15,000 first printing.

title: The Red and the Black
subtitle: A Chronicle of 1830
description: During the Bourbon Restoration, Julien Sorel disregards all moral codes as he attempts to accumulate power.

title: The Killer Angels
subtitle: A Novel of the Civil War
description: In an effort to draw out the Union Army of the Potomac, the Confederate Army invades the North, and the armies clash in a bloody battle at Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, for four days.

title: The Murders in the Rue Morgue
subtitle: The Dupin Tales
description: The story of a retired detective who is called upon to solve a perplexing pair of murders is accompanied by commentary, biographical notes, and a reading group guide.

title: Darkness Visible
subtitle: A Memoir of Madness
description: The author chronicles his descent into depression, discussing not only his own experience and recovery but also how others can find help.

title: The Fall
description: A man's confessions reveal his perception of justice and his own downfall

title: Hiroshima
description: The classic tale of the day the first atom bomb was dropped offers a haunting evocation of the memories of survivors and an appeal to the conscience of humanity

title: Mama Day
description: In a small Georgia town, Mama Day, uses her gifts as a seer and healer, but her powers are ultimately tested when her beloved niece's life hangs in the balance

title: Where I'm Calling from
subtitle: New and Selected Stories
description: A unique collection by an extraordinary writer, this collection of Carver's best spans his literary career and includes seven new works. Since his untimely death in August of 1988, Raymond Carver's popularity has increased dramatically.

title: Running Dog
description: A woman reporter and a staff assistant to an American senator learn of an erotic film shot in Hitler's Berlin bunker which was to have been sold by a man found murdered and dressed as a woman in Manhattan

title: The Names
description: In an expatriate's world of turmoil and danger, American risk analyst James Axton learns of a ritual-murder cult in the Aegean and follows the trail to its secret meanings in the ancient city of Lahore

title: What We Talk about when We Talk about Love
subtitle: Stories
description: Stories feature men and women without education, insight, or prospects, who, ironically, are too unimaginative to ever give up

title: Gideon's Trumpet
description: The story of a convict's defense of his contention that a person on trial should not be denied the assistance of counsel

title: Invisible Man
description: A black man's search for success and the American dream leads him out of college to Harlem and a growing sense of personal rejection and social invisibility

title: Lolita
description: A novel that studies the moral disintegration of a man whose obsessive desire to possess his step-daughter destroys the lives of those around him

title: Cathedral
subtitle: Stories
description: Twelve stories deal with loneliness, loss, the tragic banality of everyday life, and redemption.

title: The History of Sexuality
subtitle: Women's Decisions Concerning Contraception
description: This controversial account, by one of the greatest intellectuals of the 20th century, explores the evolving social, economic and political forces that have shaped our attitudes to sex.

title: I, Claudius
subtitle: From the Autobiography of Tiberius Claudius, Born 10 B.C., Murdered and Deified A.D. 54
description: The emperor Claudius tells of his life during the reigns of Augustus, Tiberius, and Caligula and the events that led to his rise to power in a classic novel reconstructing ancient Rome

title: No Exit, and Three Other Plays
description: English translations of four plays which dramatize the theme of man's responsibility for his own actions, by the leader of French existentialism

title: Ada, Or, Ardor, a Family Chronicle
description: Set in a "dreambright" America, at the turn of the century, the novel depicts an incestuous love affair

title: Aké
subtitle: The Years of Childhood
description: The Nigerian playwright, poet, and novelist recounts his first eleven years growing up under the influence of his parents, traditional Yoruba customs, and Christian missionaries

title: Strong Opinions
description: Interviews, articles, and editorials from the 1960s and 1970s reveal Nabokov's personal views on a range of subjects, including art, education, politics, literature, movies, and modern times

title: Mary
subtitle: A Novel
description: Lyrical prose records a young Russian exile's recollections of his first love affair

title: The Complete Monty Python's Flying Circus
subtitle: All the Words
authors: Graham Chapman;Monty Python (Comedy troupe);Terry Gilliam;Eric Idle;Terry Jones
description: Presents the complete scripts of the Monty Python television series, first shown on BBC televison from 1969 to 1974

title: The Defense
subtitle: A Novel
description: Luzhin's prodigious talent at chess earns him the title of grandmaster, but his passion soon leads to obsession, and his world falls apart during a championship match when his defense fades under his opponent's surprising strategy.

title: The Eye
description: After being humiliated by her husband, Smurov commits suicide, only to experience even greater embarrassment in the afterlife.

title: The Annotated Lolita
description: The textural discussion accompanying this novel examines the thematic and technical elements which make it a literary classic

title: Maus II
subtitle: a survivor's tale : and here my troubles began
description: In a comic-book-style tale of the author's parents, Vladek and Anja, Vladek survives Auschwitz, is reunited with Anja, and sires young Art

title: The Best of Roald Dahl
description: Stories relate the macabre exploits of an assortment of comical and grotesque characters from all walks of life

title: The Stories of Vladimir Nabokov
description: A collection of 65 stories about human relations, human nature, and political satire includes 13 first-time English translations

title: Hit Men
subtitle: Power Brokers and Fast Money Inside the Music Business
description: An inside look at the multibillion-dollar music industry examines the business practices of the big record labels and includes profiles of the kingpins of the industry

title: A Year in Provence
description: A month-by-month account of the author's experience in the first year of restoring a two-centuries old stone farmhouse in back country Provence, France.

title: The Origin of Satan
description: A study of the role of the devil in biblical and modern times theorizes that dissident social gorups that resisted Christianity, such as pagans and Jews, were typically portrayed as demons and therefore established as threats. Reprint. 60,000 first printing.

title: A History of the World in 10 1/2 Chapters
description: Offers an idiosyncratic, revisionist history of life on planet Earth, from a playful account of Noah by a stowaway on the Ark, to the spiritual odyssey of a American astronaut

title: Go Down, Moses
description: Set in mythical Yoknapatawpha County, seven interrelated stories deal with the complex, changing relationships between Blacks and whites and between man and nature

title: Light in August
description: In a novel about hopeless perseverance in the face of mortality, guileless Lena Grove searches for the father of her unborn child, Reverend Hightower is plagued by visions of Confederate horsemen, and drifter Joe Christmas is consumed by his mixed ancestry

title: Chilly Scenes of Winter
description: This is the story of a love-smitten Charles; his friend Sam, the Phi Beta Kappa and former coat salesman; and Charles' mother, who spends a lot of time in the bathtub feeling depressed.

title: The Beggar Maid
subtitle: Stories of Flo and Rose
description: Originally published as: Who do you think you are? 1978.

title: A Midwife's Tale
subtitle: The Life of Martha Ballard, Based on Her Diary, 1785-1812
description: Presents the life of Martha Ballard, a midwife in Maine during the eighteenth century, by drawing on the detailed diary she kept for twenty-seven years of her life

title: The Woman in the Dunes
description: The inhabitants of a remote seaside village imprison a Japanese biologist in a deep sand pit

title: The Rebel
subtitle: An Essay on Man in Revolt
description: The author traces the ways in which the theories of philosophers such as Rousseau, Hegel and Marx have been misused.

title: The Art of Fiction
subtitle: Notes on Craft for Young Writers
description: A guide to creative writing examines diverse facets of writing technique, and contains analyses of works by writers from Homer to Mark Twain

title: Success
description: Soaring with malicious poetry and almost unbearably accurate in its characterizations, Martin Amis turns Success into a sort of Jacobean revenge comedy. Its antagonists are two mismatched foster brothers who perform a merciless tango of class hatred, sexual rivalry, and disappointed love.

title: Crime and Punishment
subtitle: A Novel in Six Parts with Epilogue
description: A man must endure relentless physical and metal punishments as retribution for his act of murder

title: Hype and Glory
description: The author of "Adventures in the Screen Trade" provides an inside look at the Cannes Film Festivals and the Miss America Pageant from his unique perspective as a judge, offering anecdotes about the judging process

title: The Heidi Chronicles and Other Plays
description: Three plays deal with recent college graduates deciding what to do with their lives, a woman trying to be a successful executive and mother, and an art historian changing with the times from the sixties to the eighties

title: Dispatches
description: A documentation of the day-to-day realities of the war in Vietnam experienced by men on patrol, under siege at Khe Sanh, strapped into helicopters, and faced with continuing nightmares after their return to the United States

title: Touching the Rock
subtitle: An Experience of Blindness
description: An intensely personal exploration of blindness reveals a world of sound and echo, of people without faces, of the strange relationship between waking and dreaming, and of new perceptions of nature, personality, and human experience

title: The Foundation Trilogy
